Headlines.Headline: Denbury buys Encore, Potentially Creating a CO2 Injecting Giant

PARAGRAPH.#text: On Sunday, Denbury Resources Inc. agreed to buy Encore Acquisition Co. for $3.25 billion. The deal brings together two oil-focused, U.S.-centric independent energy producers.What's more, the deal brings together two companies at the forefront of figuring out how to collect manmade carbon dioxide and ship it to aging oilfields, where it is can be used in enhanced-oil recovery operations to coax additional barrels out of the earth. Denbury is building a carbon-dioxide pipeline from Louisiana to south of Houston. Encore is looking to do a similar project up in the Rockies.We caught up with Tracy Evans, Denbury's president and chief operating officer.Environmental Capital: You are building a 320-mile carbon-dioxide pipeline along the Gulf Coast. Encore wants to build a 200-mile carbon-dioxide pipeline in the Rockies. What's the point of moving all this carbon dioxide around?Mr. Evans: "The point of moving it around is obviously to produce the oil. It is oil that would not otherwise be producible. The oil that remains after a water flood is essential immobile. The CO2 goes in and mixes with that oil, making it mobile. Therefore it can be produced." Environmental Capital: Do you envision a carbon-dioxide pipeline infrastructure in the future? How big can it get...
